{"attack":true,"cited_input_aliases":[],"claim":"The target names a mechanism but its forbidden case is not a concrete, datable observation that could realistically have obtained.","counterexample":null,"grounds":"The standard requires forbidden cases to be 'concrete observations which could realistically have obtained (a record, an event, a datable pattern).' The target's forbidden case — 'Archaeological evidence of robust, independent local grain storage or non-palatial craft production persisting through the transition period in the core collapse zones' — is not a single concrete observation, record, event, or datable pattern. It is a vague category of evidence described at a high level of abstraction, lacking specification of what site, what date range, what specific artifact assemblage, or what documentary record would constitute such evidence. A concrete forbidden case would name, for example, 'Excavation at Pylos revealing a non-palatial granary with radiocarbon dates spanning 1200–1150 BCE' or 'Linear B tablets from Knossos recording independent local textile production after 1190 BCE.' The target's formulation fails the specificity requirement of clause (2).","target_alias":"A1"}